        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "The ability to specify column aliases in a similar manner to table names.\n\n_(This summarises the discussion from the mailing list with Bill Karwin)_\n\nExample:\n\n{code}\n$adapter->select()->from('mytable', array(\n    'alias1' => 'colA',\n    'alias2' => new Zend_Db_Expr('fn(colB)'),\n    'colC',\n    'colD AS alias3',\n    'alias4' => 'fncall2()',\n    'fncall3() AS alias5'\n));\n{code}\n\nIt will work by checking the keys of the columns array,\nany key that {{is_string()}} will be taken to be a column alias.\n\nIf a string matches the regular expression: {noformat}\/^(.+)\\s+AS\\s+(.+)$\/i{noformat}\nThen the string should be converted into the alias => column form.  It\nshould be very rare that a column name matches that pattern.  This will\nmake it easier for people to use {{\"column AS alias\"}} syntax in a simple\nstring.\n\nAlso if a column string matches the regular expression: {noformat}\/.+\\(.*\\)\/{noformat}\nThen the string should be converted into a Zend_Db_Expr.  It should be\nvery rare that a column name matches that pattern.  This will make it\neasier for people to use common cases like {{\"COUNT\\(*\\)\"}}.\n"
        },
